column63: Human Error; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column169: At 17:03 on 9/12/2024, ISO tank CXTU 101946 was reported Ieaking at the Kansas City Southern(DBA CPKC) IFG intermodal ramp located in Kansas City, MO. CPKC Hazmat Department mobilized to the ramp, along with a response contractor, to mitigate the release. Upon arrival, responders found all security seals in place. A small stream of liquid was emanating from the bottom outlet valve secondary closure cap, which was found hand tight. The primary closure"butterfly" valve was found slightly open. Additionally, the Internal bottom outlet valve's security seal was applied in such a way as to prevent the valve from fully closing. The crew tightened the secondary closure cap on the bottom outlet valve and secured the primary closure"butterfly" valve to stop the release. Due to the nature of the product, responders elected to make shipper notification and request permission to remove the security seals in order to determine the extent of the product lost. On 9/13/2024, permission was received from the shipper to remove the security seals. The crew returned to IFG to complete investigation. Upon return, the manway was opened to inspect outage on CXTU101946. All manway bolts were found loose. The Iadlng outage was approximately 2 feet. Estimate for Iading release is 40 gallons. The secondary closure cap was removed and found with a defective gasket. Responders replaced the gasket. The cap was installed tool tight and security seal installed in the closed position. Also, the internal bottom outlet valve security seal that was holding the valve in the partially open position was removed and a new security seal was properly installed holding the valve In the closed position. No security seals were removed from the butterfly valve, but an additional security seal was properly installed to hold this valve in the closed position. Once secured, CXTU101946 was released back into transportation. Additional DOT Cause Code: What Failed: 121, How Failed: 308, Cause of Failure: 508. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best Information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car loads therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR)(DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a rootcause Investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCSR.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Carl Akins, KCSR Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column169: Driver was loading trailer with Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5%(16140525) at K2 when it overflowed the top of the trailer. Scales were closed due an unrelated incident so the load quantity calculation had to be completed manually. Driver did not use an inch stick to confirm initial quantity before loading, resulting in an overflow. Driver stated less than 10 gallons went into the containment area. No exposure and no off-site release. Release was contained and cleaned up to operator's satisfaction.
column170: Driver was required to retrain on the loading procedure. If the scales are down, drivers are to wait until scale is available if possible. If not, drivers are required to use an inch stick to confirm physical quantity in trailer prior to loading. ^ I

column169: On September 18, 2024, Cowan Intermodal Group, LLC contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) of a release in Morgantown, WV. It was reported an undetermined amount of Belclene® 200 was due to a single vehicle accident was caused by the truck striking a guardrail and flipping onto its side, the release impacted soil, asphalt and a nearby storm drain. It was also reported the impacted area was 60ft by 30ft and approximately 5000 gallons of product. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors contacted DOT to provide traffic control to excavate the damaged travel lines. Excavation was complete asphalt milling and a surface scrape that measured 85ft by 8ft area.  2 roll offs containing impacted soil and 3 roll off boxes of asphalt milling were collected. There were 16 totes total involved. The product was vacuumed out of the bottom of the trailer into 1 vac truck and 9 different totes for transfer. The 16 damaged totes were placed in 2 roll off boxes and staged at a near by DOT site. All waste generated was taken off-site for proper disposal.

column169: AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY, WE DISCOVERED ONE STEEL DRUM DAMAGED AND LEAKING. Tank truck was being loaded with 45,000 lbs of formaldehyde distillate(13% concentration). Toward the end of loading, a high-level probe should have stopped the pump and prevented over-filling of the truck. The probe was tripped, but the automatic valve responded more slowly than optimal resulting in a spill of about 10 gallons(100-lbs) that flowed down the side of the truck on to the truck loading pad, and then toward the secondary'containment ditch to the east of the pad. The truck and loading pad were washed down with water Into the containment ditch. From there, it drained into a sump and was conveyed by an in-place submersible pump to a recycle storage tank. Investigation found that the high-level probe triggered immediately on contact with the solution, but that the automatic valve closed slowly, and that the truck tank had a taller than usual dome-lid extension.
column170: A more responsive automatic valve has been ordered and received, and will be installed in the near future. In addition, the length of the probe will be extended an additional couple of inches in order to enable the probe to reach further past the truck dome.

9/28/24 BNSF train crews noticed vapor emanating from the top of the RCRX 2821 while moving the car in Dore, ND.  The crew isolated the car and notifications were made.  BNSF contractor Pinnacle Engineering responded to inspect the car and found liquid hydrochloric acid on the liquid line flange as confirmed by pH strips.  The liquid line flange bolts were found to be less than finger tight and easily moved by hand.  Responders tightened and secured the flange and neutralized the acid.  Other bolts on the valves and pressure plate were inspected and tightened further using crescent wrenches.  The car was held pending receipt of an approved OTMA for further movement.

On 09/18/2024, while working in MP31 track, Presidents Island Yard, Memphis, TN, FRA Inspector Mr. Ken Barefield observed a dark liquid leaking from the top of PROX70548, (Load, Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid N.O.S., (Benzo (b) Fluoranthene, Benzo (A) Pyrene, Contain S), UN3082) down the side of the tank car to the ground. FRA Inspector Barefield notified CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) Vaughan. FRA Inspector Barefield advised that 6 of the 8 nuts on the manway cover bolts were ?less than tool tight?. CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) Vaughan performed an inspection of the tank car and found the 6 of 8 nuts on the manway cover bolts to be ?less than tool tight?. Upon further inspection, the manway cover was opened, and the manway cover gasket was observed to be broken. The shipper applied cable seal # 471609 was observed in place and intact at the time of the release. The responding CN Dangerous Goods Officer (DGO) removed the existing manway cover gasket segments, then cleaned the sealing surfaces of the manway cover and the rim nozzle and were inspected for metal burs. Product residue on the manway cover and rim nozzle was removed using a cleaner and absorbents. A new rim nozzle gasket made of ?Viton A?, was properly installed and secured using a 18" pipe wrench to tighten the manway cover bolts ?tool tight?. Product spillage on the sides of the tank car, loader platform handrails and walking boards along with other safety appliances were cleaned using a cleaning solution recommended by the consignee and absorbents. Tank car was secured and released to CN Transportation for delivery to consignee. New Seals # CNDG 200031-Manway, CNDG 000980-Protective Housing, CNDG 200033-Bottom Outlet Valve Cap,  CNDG 000984-Bottom Outlet Valve Handle and Securing Pin, were applied.

column169: File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value. On September 10, 2024, Daniel Perkins, FRA Hazmat Inspector, conducted an inspection at the CPKC Muskego Yard in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. During inspection of tank car TILX 318532, Mr. Perkins observed wetness inside the interior of the protective housing. The wetness evaporated instantly. Further examination revealed that that four of four liquid valve flange nuts were loose which allowed for vapor to release from the assembly. A CPKC Contractor responded to the incident and was able to tighten the fiange nuts, stopping the leak.
column170: The SOO LINE RAILROAD COMPANY(DBA CPI(C) notified shipper of this release. Continued emphasis with Offerors/St ® pers Is made to conduct thorough Inspections prior to movement in order to reduce valve failures in the field. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a. k.a. package closure Issues such as this), the shipper Is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with SOO Line Railroad(Please direct your root cause Investigation results and corrective actions to Ed Dankbar, SOO Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. (NAR: 270)

XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN1760 GF Clean 1052 release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released. The drum was damaged because of improper securement as the drums were not properly strapped to the pallet and shifted off it. The material impacted an 8' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 11' x 6' area of the concrete lot below. Absorbents & sodium bicarb were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. The damaged drum was containerized into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All impacted absorbents and debris were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 1246 EST on Tuesday, September 24, 2024, a report was made to the Whitewater Township Fire Department of a railcar off-gassing with a spray paint-like odor. The reported railcar, PROX 24041, was documented to contain Styrene Monomer and was located at a railyard near Cleves, OH (39.171181° , -84.763446°). The railcar was staged in the Central Railroad of Indiana Cleves Yard. The Whitewater Township Fire Department arrived on site around 1314 to begin cooling efforts. CTEH, SPSI, GHD, HEPACO, Enviro-Serve, and EnviroScience were mobilized to' perform emergency response services. On 9/26/2024 at 1927 EST the evacuation order for Whitewater Township was lifted.  5x(5+1+0)x(5+4) = NARRI 270

column169: On September 9, 2024, at 1148 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Charlotte, North Carolina regarding the release of Champion Muriatic Acid. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1 gallon of Champion Muriatic Acid (UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid, 8, II) from (1) 1-gallon poly jug. The release was caused by a multi vehicle accident and impacted the cardboard packaging of other cargo, the trailer floor, and a 1ft x 5ft area of asphalt beneath the trailer. The local fire department solidified the release in the trailer, then contractors neutralized the asphalt, the trailer floor, and the impacted cardboard boxes. The undamaged cargo inside impacted boxes were unboxed, then wrapped and repalletized. Contractors then cleaned the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DFs and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed absorbent rags to the impacted drum, and neutralized the exterior. A replacement cap was then used to fix the drum. The drum was staged on the truck for future shipping. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon vented drum and was taken to the Columbiana terminal for future disposal.

column169: On September 30, 2024, at 1015 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal UFN experienced release of UN1760 “Tower NG 7100” from a 275-gallon poly tote. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The impacted area was then cleaned with Spilfyter KolorSafe Base Neutralizer and Floor Dry. The damaged tote, impacted absorbents, pads, and PPE were then collected into (7) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column63: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column169: An spill occurred at Veolia's ten-day transit facility located in Westland, MI during a routine drum transfer operation. An employee was using a drum picker to load a drum onto a trailer when the situation occurred. As the drum was being maneuvered into position, it inadvertently made contact with the side of the trailer. Upon impact, it was discovered that a sharp piece of metal protruding from the trailer's side had punctured the drum, resulting in a dime-sized hole. The employee immediately noticed the damage and the subsequent leak. It was estimated that approximately two gallons of the drum's contents had spilled as a result of the puncture.
column170: This incident highlights the importance of regular equipment inspections and the need for careful handling during transfer operations. It also underscores the potential hazards that can arise from seemingly minor equipment defects, such as protruding metal on trailer sides. The Veolia management team reviewed with employees the importance of hazard recognition and having awareness of their surrounding while loading/unloading.

column169: At 1134 ET, XPO terminal LTY notified ERTS of a cargo refused shipment that took place 08/2024. The terminal will reach out to the shipper to see if shipper would like the product returned to them. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. The terminal used oil dri as an absorbent and a 30-gallon poly drum for the waste.  The waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

On September 9, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2265 was shipped with faulty packaging and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the dock floor and pallet below. On 9/5/2024 at approximately 1730, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5028110 at the station location in Stockton, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consists of one metal cylinder packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered making a hissing sound.  Further investigation revealed the cylinder was accidentally discharging inside of the box.  The cause is the discharge is unknown.  The shipment was isolated from other packages and is being held pending an FAA investigation.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a release of LIMA-6, from a 275-gallon poly tote. The tote was crushed by other freight due to improper loading. A contractor was dispatched and observed a 0.5-gallon release isolated to the top of the tote. The contractor cleaned-up the release and performed a tote transfer. Four 55-gallon DF’s were generated as waste for disposal containing impacted oil dry, impacted PPE, and cut-up tote pieces. XPO will manage all waste generated from the spill response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

On 09/20/2024, at 0857 hours, CSX personnel reported UTLX 208840, a loaded tank car containing Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Poet Bioprocessing, was notified via Ambipar (Report #20240920-01-02787). CSX Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials Rob James responded to the scene and found five of eight manway cover bolts less than tool tight.  Mr. James inspected the car to ensure there were no notable defects to the manway cover, gasket, or nozzle, and secured all manway cover bolts tool tight to secure the product release.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Jared Ayers (316-213-2805). Upon proper securement the car was released for transportation.

Driver noticed product leaking as he was taking a break and notified supervision. The leak was coming from the crash/spill box area. The driver began to drive the equipment and was instructed by supervision to stop driving the equipment and pull into a safe area. The driver stopped and the local municipality's fire department and EHS arrived at the scene, as well as, a third party environmental clean-up company, McCutcheon's.  The HCL was off-loaded into 10 totes, which were loaded into straight truck with a lift gate, approximately 1,600gallons were off-loaded into another Univar tanker and taken to the Univar Altoona plant, and the remaining product remained in the original tanker. The 10 totes and original tanker were taken to the Univar Solutions Bunola plant.  Approximately 20 gallons of HCL was released.  Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection conducted a site visit and provided a satisfactory rating for the response and clean up.  PADEP #1410124
column170: Retrain drivers on the importance of completing a thorough walk around of the equipment when they stop in route for a rest/lunch break.  Conductivity testing when CTMV is at capacity.

column43: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column169: BAE Systems Ordnance Systems Inc. (OSI) is the operating contractor for Holston Army Ammunition  Plant (HSAAP) located at 4509 West Stone Drive in Kingsport, Hawkins County, Tennessee. On  September 13, 2024 a hose rupture during offload of a strong nitric acid tanker resulted in a  release of acid to the environment. A description of the event is outlined below:  The truck driver and operators started the transfer and then moved to observe from a safe location  per standard operating procedure. Approximately 10 minutes after the transfer started, personnel  observed a NOx cloud and nitric acid spray coming from the back of the tanker. After the wind  shifted, the driver made the decision to approach the tanker and activate the emergency stop,  ending the release. Upon further investigation after the incident, personnel found the transfer  hose had failed.  The total amount of nitric acid released from the tanker was 20,988 pounds. It is estimated that  approximately 10,494 pounds of nitric acid drained to the spill basin for the tanker pad and into  the wastewater collection system. Approximately 10,494 pounds sprayed onto the ground next to the  tanker pad. None of the nitric acid traveled to the stormwater channels. Approximately 105 pounds  of NOx was released during the event. A hazmat contractor was promptly hired to clean up the release.
column170: BAE Systems is working with the supplier to define an improved process to ensure adequate hoses of the appropriate materials of construction are used for all transfers moving forward.

column169: On September 10, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of printer ink was punctured in transit and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the trailer interior, under cage, and roadway beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the site. EWI Scraped the inside of the trailer using hand tools and degreaser. crews placed absorbents on the trailer floor to soak up all degreaser. The gravel underneath the trailer was shoveled using hand tools until no product was left on the ground. With approval from R+L the driver was sent to the St. Louis, MO, Terminals wash bay to remediate the exterior of the trailer. All spent absorbents, as well as any damaged drums were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum which was taken back to the Springfield, MO, R+L terminal where it was staged for future disposal

ONE AIR PACKAGE SHIPPED IN JULY 2024 FROM BRAZIL TO THE UNITED KINGDOM WAS RELEASED TO UPS ACCESS POINT, POUND LANE CONVENIENCE, POUND LANE 6, KT19 8RY EPSOM, UNITED KINGDOM ON 15-JULY-2024.  THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT PICK UP THE PACKAGE, THUS THE PACKAGE WAS RELEASED BACK TO UPS FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER ON 20-AUGUST-2024. DURING THE RETURN TO SHIPPER PROCESS UNDER RETURN TRACKING NUMBER 1ZC509A80406240368, X-RAY REVEALS ONE BOTTLE OF FLAMMABLE COLOGNE. SDS OBTAINED FROM THE MANUFACTURER REVEALS THE PRODUCT IS CLASSIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS DURING AIR TRANSPORTATION. THE PACKAGE HAD FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT WITHOUT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS FROM BRAZIL TO THE UNITED KINGDOM PRIOR TO THE UNDECLARED DISCOVERY. UPSCO WAS MADE AWARE OF THE UNDECLARED INCIDENT ON 19-NOVEMBER-2024.

Tank car CGTX 31178 was found in the West Colton Yard in Bloomington, CA with diesel down the sides of the tank car and between the manway and the combination housing. After assessment it was determined that the manway swing bolts were over tightened causing the manway to be misaligned, also, the safety eye bolt was offset/bowed from being over torqued causing product to release. The manway gasket was inspected, and no issues where found. The tank car manway was reset, and the swing bolts were secured properly. Contractor cleaned off all diesel impacted areas on the tank car.
column170: Spoke with shipper about proper securement procedures.

column169: On September 17, 2024, four (4) 5-gallon cans of UN3098 were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior and loading dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel utilized hand tools, absorbent pads, a Hudson Sprayer, Sodium Metabisulfite, and Soda Ash to remediate the impacted trailer interior and loading dock floor. All impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 95-gallon overpack and two (2) 55-gallon drums.   R+L requested for the crew to return later in the day. Three (3) additional 5-gallon jerrycans of product were damaged with approximately one half (0.5) gallon of product released to the pallet, nearby freight, and loading dock floor. Sodium Metabisulfite, and Soda Ash were utilized to remediate the site. The spent absorbents were then collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum.

column169: At approximately 2000 a group arrived with 2 different airway bills linked to a single PAL accounting when we inquired if any of the shipments contained Dangerous Goods they assured us they were only shipping clothing  and a couple of cell phones. We explained that cellphones are considered dangerous goods due to the lithium-ion batteries inside. The customer demanded that we load it on the flight because they are okay. When we refused to do so they stated they would take the cellphones out. However during the screening process the screener noticed cellphones and 2 tablet found the cellphones were wrapped in writing paper. The charging cord was wrapped around the phone. I ultimately decided to refuse the shipment due to the undeclared dangerous goods and the way they were ____ .

The shipment consisted of one plastic container packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered leaking from the bottom of the box. The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column63: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column169: On September 6, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of Swisher Hercules was punctured and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the Swisher Hercules-impacted dock floor and swept them in with hand tools. Crews neutralized the absorbents and spilled materials and utilized pH test strips. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and one (1) damaged pail of Swisher Hercules was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column63: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column169: On September 13, 2024, at 1111 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Hebron, Ohio regarding the release of STRONTIUM CHROMATE 176. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1 pound of Strontium Chromate 176 (UN3077, 9, III) from (1) 1000 lb. supersack. The release was caused by a collapsed pallet and impacted a 1ft x 6ft area of the trailer floor. Contractors were able to successfully patch the hole in the punctured supersack then placed it in a lined gaylord. The release was collected with the proper PPE and placed in a metal drum. Another supersack that was undamaged but was on top of a collapsed pallet was also placed into a lined gaylord as a precaution. All cargo was unloaded, unwrapped, restacked and rewrapped onto new pallets before being reloaded onto the trailer. All waste was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DMs and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.
column199: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column63: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column169: On September 9, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1148 was punctured in transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services. LC who dispatched a crew from Mid-South Environmental Services (MSES) to remediate the impacted site. MSES personnel plugged the leaking drum and placed it into one 95-gallon overpack. Chem pads were placed to clean the bulk liquid and spill tackle was deployed to all affected areas. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. Both drums were taken offsite for future disposal.

column169: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-B. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART AND DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE AUXILARY/VENT CAP ON A 5-GAL POLY PAIL WAS LOOSE BY A FULL ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column169: AT THE UPS PORTLAND FACILITY WE RESPONDED TO AN AIR PACKAGE THAT WAS LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED FOUR X ONE GALLON CANS OF FLAMMABLE CLASSIC EXPRESS STAIN WITH ONE CAN LEAKING. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM SOUTH CAROLINA USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER J5H558, WHITE, 4115 DORCHESTER RD, NORTH CHARLESTON SC 29405-7466.

Our driver loaded the drums into truck at the shipper's facility.  Driver, after securing drums, failed to secure a loose pallet jack in the back of this truck.  In transit, the pallet jack shifted and rolled into 1A1 steel drum containing antifreeze.  Drum damage resulted in loss of 15 gallons of material into back of truck and onto private property of subsequent customer.  Complete cleanup was conducted by our company, in-house.
column170: This matter resulted in an Incident Review Call including corporate leadership.  Driver has been entered into progressive discipline system and been assigned to extensive re-training with a focus on package and lading securement.  This training will also be assigned to other personnel with intent of preventing reoccurrence.

On 9/9/24 rail car GIMX516236 arrived at the facility with 2 IBC containers that were found leaking material onto the rail car. Absorbent were put down and a crew was call out to address the release. The crew arrived and added containments pans under the area that was leaking and more absorbent was applied. The crew need more equipment and returned on 9/1/24 at 0900. They added more absorbents to the containers to absorb any free liquids that were left and addressed the container doors checking the seals and retightening them. The crew then cleaned the rail car and the outside of the boxes. They were completed and leaving the scene at 1630.

column169: On September 3, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of sulfuric acid was punctured by falling freight and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior and surrounding freight. The release impacted the asphalt parking lot and ditch that is in the center of the parking lot. Emergency response contractor HEPACO arrived on site and performed an initial clean up and collected an estimated 11,000 gallons of Liquid waste from the ditch and placed it into a frac-tank. The soil ditch area is pending remediation. No storm drains were reported impacted by the release.

column169: On September 17, 2024, at 1141 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Lithonia, Georgia regarding the release of NALCO® BT-3011 BOILER WATER TREATMENT.  Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 260 gallons of Nalco BT-3011 Boiler Water Treatment (Sodium Hydroxide Solution, UN1824, 8, III) from (1) IBC plastic tote. The release was caused by a puncture and impacted the trailer floor, and multiple small areas of concrete as the trailer was in motion, that were unrecoverable. The residual material in the damaged tote was neutralized and solidified with absorbents, the damaged tote was cut up, then the trailer was neutralized and cleaned. Contractors also confirmed a 1ft x 6inch area of soil was impacted. Contractors were able to collect the impacted soil without complication. All waste was containerized in (4) 55-gallon DFs and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

On September 3, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3266 was crushed in transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel discovered that one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3266 washer fluid and one (1) 5-gallon pail of non-regulated washer fluid were damaged and released approximately three (3) gallons of product. TLE personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the sulfuric acid-impacted impacted dock floor. The damaged pail and all impacted debris were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums

Operations Supervisor II Lloyd Conner contacted safety to report a Hazardous Spill. Lloyd stated that they were unloading trailer 570971 when they noticed a pallet that was damaged and leaking onto the trailer floor. Lloyd stated that the pallet contained 5-gallon pails of UN1760, Corrosive liquids,  n.o.s., (Potassium hydroxide and ethanolamine solutions, 8, PG II. Lloyd stated that another pallet was loaded on top of the pallet containing the 5-gallon pails and crushed one of the pails on the bottom resulting in a spillage on the trailer floor and the dock plate. Lloyd stated that he set a pe rimeter around the spill and the back of the trailer. Lloyd stated that no waterways were impacted. Safety contacted CURA and spoke with Brandon Baumann for remediation.  ~

XPO Logistics terminal LEP experienced a UN1866 Bulldog Adhesion Promoter release from 2 boxes each containing (6) 1-quart metal bottles. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 6 quarts of product released to a 3’ x 5’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 4’ area of the concrete lot below. The cans were damaged as a result of being crushed due to stacking/improper loading. The (8) damaged cans were placed into a 55-gallon metal drum. All impacted cardboard, pads, and absorbents used to clean the spill were placed into a second 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The external overpack marked box was dented on the sides and two edges when it was discovered. The flaps on the underside of the box, were loose, as the water activated tape that was supposed to secure them shut was frayed. When the box was inspected , the granules were visible at the bottom interior of the box. The lid of the inner plastic pail had a divot gouged on the edge circumference.

The waste was containerized in a 10-Gallon poly drum and staged for terminal personnel to manage.

During unloading operations at the Menomonee Falls 10-Day Facility, staff discovered a leak from a 5-gallon container of lithium preserved in mineral oil inside a trailer. The spill was limited to less than 2 gallons and remained confined within the trailer. Upon investigation, it was determined that the leak occurred due to improper securing of the load, which allowed the containers to shift during transportation. The spill was remediated by trained Veolia personnel and the container was properly closed.

At 03:39 EST on 9/19, XPO-XMI contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 25 gallons of "776 Inhibitor Solution" from a 55-gallon metal drum. The drum was punctured by a forklift at the XMI dock. The material is reported to be smoking on the dock. ERTS instructed the terminal personnel to leave the spill as-is, and not to interact with the material further. Any personnel with a potential for exposure should be removed from the area and exposures should be reported to the immediate supervisor.  The contractors confirmed the spill is contained with oil dry, overpacked the 55-gallon metal drum into (1) 95-gallon metal drum, impacted speedy dri into (3) 55-gallon metal drums.  The waste was staged for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: AN AIR PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG TO BELGIUM WAS DISCOVERED EMITTING SMOKE WHILE TRAVELING ON THE CONVEYOR SYSTEM IN THE UPS DIEGEM BELGIUM FACILITY.  THE PACKAGE BEGAN GENERATING HEAVY SMOKE TRIGGERING THE FIRE ALARM SYSTEM AND AN EVACUATION OF THE BUILDING. WHEN THE LOCAL FIRE BRIGADE ARRIVED THE BATTERY EVENT HAD SLOWED DOWN ALLOWING THE PACKAGE TO BE SECURED BY THE FIRE BRIGADE IN A WATER TANK TO PREVENT REACTIVATION OF THE EVENT.  THE INCIDENT PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS UN3480, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965. THE PACKAGE HAD AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AND HAD PREVIOUSLY PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT IN HONG KONG.  THE PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON SEPTEMBER 25, 2024, UNDER REPORT 1411829.

On 9/19/24 at 2:45am, shortly after refueling at Loves Truck Stop in Port Allen, LA, an OxyChem truck driver noticed liquid coming from the drain tube for the trailer’s dome. The driver immediately pulled to the side of the road to inspect the trailer. Upon inspection, three of the dome lugs were less than tool tight. The driver immediately notified OxyChem dispatch and OxyChem management. A third-party technician responded and tightened the lugs. The driver performed a slosh test and discovered the dome was still not sealed. The OxyChem Response Team responded and temporarily secured the dome to prevent leakage during movement to a nearby truck repair facility. The OxyChem Response team then replaced the dome gasket, which resolved the issue. The LA State Police Hazmat was notified. There are no injuries, exposures, damage, or environmental impact.
column170: During the response, it was discovered the dome gasket was missing. Further investigation revealed that the customer site on the previous delivery this trailer was used on had opened the dome hatch to retrieve a product sample. This is where we believe the dome gasket went missing. The trailer is currently being washed and dried so that an internal inspection can be done to determine if the dome gasket fell off into the tank during the previous delivery.  In the meantime, OxyChem Technical Service group has reached out to this customer site to request that they no longer open the dome lids of OxyChem trailers for numerous reasons. Further actions are being discussed to determine accountability measures of the above request.

The impacted wood, spent absorbent pads, spent granular absorbents, and all UN3214 impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon vented poly drum

column169: Another IAC arranged the delivery of the freight by shipper to our facility on Sep 18th, 2024. As an IAC-CCSF, we were advised to screen & transfer the freight to the air carrier of the shipment for airlines booking made via the other IAC. There was a pick up truck which arrived to our facility to deliver the crate and when the driver was asked to provide proper identification and sign our check-in sheet, he left w/o either. We, UAC INT'L, notified the IAC about this incident. Due to the suspicious delivery activity, we opened the crate which we did not accept on behalf of the IAC and discovered 3 loose Lithium Ion Batteries in the crate. We notified the IAC and DFW TSA of the incident accordingly.
column170: We, UAC INT'L, did not accept the cargo for air transport. It remains in our custody in our warehouse for TSA/FAA follow up.

On September 29, 2024, at 1107 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Elgin, Nebraska regarding the release of Acetone. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 16 ounces of Acetone (UN1090, 3, II) from (1) 275-gallon plastic tote. The release was reportedly due to a faulty nozzle, and there was no impact to the trailer floor as all material was caught on a rag. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Contactors transferred all remaining material to a new 275-gallon plastic tote. The damaged tote was the only waste generated from this incident which was then taken off site by the contractor for proper disposal.

All spent absorbents, pads, and the damaged pails, were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal.

column169: On September 9, 2024, five (5) five-gallon pails of primer were dropped during unloading and released approximately twenty (20) gallons of primer to the asphalt. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from NRC Gulf Environmental Services, Inc. (NRC Gulf) to remediate the impacted site.  NRC Gulf placed all damaged pails into seven (7) lined 55-gallon drums. Granular absorbents were placed onto all primer impacted areas. The crew swept up all loose absorbents with hand tools. A pressure washing system was used on all stained concrete and a vac truck was utilized to retain any loose water. All seven (7) waste drums were taken offsite and staged at the Milton, Florida R+L terminal. All waste water was taken with the crew to be disposed of on a later date.

column43: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column169: On 9/25/2024 at approximately 1030, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 957951 at the ramp facility in Sacramento, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box, containing two fiberboard boxes with a fire extinguisher in each inner box.  The shipment was discovered showing a powder residue on the outer package and on the aircraft floor.  Further investigation revealed that the shipment contained fire extinguishers that were missing the secure pin.  Additionally, the package was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork on the outermost pacakge.  The shipment is being held, pending in FAA investigation.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Veolia personnel visited Santa Clara Valley Medical Center to collect various types of universal waste. Among the items were two 5-gallon pails containing lithium-ion batteries. The Veolia team carefully inspected each battery to ensure there was no bulging or damage, and verified that the terminals were properly protected with tape.  The following morning, as Veolia employees were unloading waste from a box truck for trans-loading at Veolia's intransit facility, one worker noticed smoke emanating from one of the pails containing lithium-ion batteries. Acting swiftly, the employee removed the smoking 5-gallon pail from the truck and isolated it outdoors. The affected battery was allowed to complete its reaction process safely.  Subsequently, the remaining batteries were separated and thoroughly re-examined. As a precautionary measure, each lithium-ion battery was individually bagged, and packed with fire suppressant media. Following this incident, all lithium-ion batteries were treated as damaged or defective and packaged in accordance with the 49 CFR 173.185(f) regulations. The second pail of lithium batteries underwent the same rigorous re-examination and packaging process to ensure safety and compliance.
column170: Following the incident, a thorough investigation was conducted. The findings revealed that the battery in question had several wires with compromised insulation. This damage allowed exposed sections of the wires to come into contact with one another, potentially causing a short circuit and triggering the battery's reaction.  In response to this event, Veolia has committed to taking the following actions:  1. Conduct a comprehensive review of the incident with all relevant employees. 2. Implement additional training to emphasize the importance of inspecting wiring conditions on batteries. 3. Reinforce existing lithium battery shipping guidelines through refresher courses for all staff involved in handling and transporting these materials.  These measures aim to prevent similar incidents in the future and ensure the continued safe handling and transportation of lithium batteries.

On September 2, 2024 at 0545, a Conyers driver was offloading a liquid oxygen trailer at a remote customer site in northern Georgia. Toward the end of the offload, the driver noticed a small fire beginning near the pump area of the trailer. The driver walked around to the outer side of the trailer to investigate and noticed the fire increasing. The driver immediately shut down the offload, and secured the trailer and customer tanks as he exited the area. Please note that at the time of the event, we were unsure that there was an unintentional release of product. Due to the evacuation, we proactively called the NRC, but have determined that there was no release of product.
column170: Root Cause Analysis is in progress, have determined that there was not an unintentional release of product.

column169: At Veolia's ten-day facility in Henderson, CO, staff identified a leaking trailer in the parking lot storage area. Upon discovery, the trailer was promptly relocated to a loading dock for further inspection and handling. During the offloading process, it was determined that a drum within the trailer had sustained damage. Specifically, a nail puncture had created a pinhole leak at the bottom of the drum. As a result of this damage, approximately one gallon of liquid had escaped.  Upon conducting a thorough investigation into the incident, the root cause of the leak was identified. It was discovered that the drum had been compromised due to a structural issue with its supporting pallet. Specifically, a nail was found to be protruding from the pallet on which the drum had been placed. This protruding nail had punctured the bottom of the drum during transit or handling, creating the pinhole leak that led to the subsequent fluid release.  Immediate action was taken to address the situation. The compromised drum was placed into an overpack container to prevent any additional leakage. Concurrently, a thorough clean-up operation was conducted to remove all spilled liquid from the affected area, ensuring no residual contamination remained.
column170: The finding highlights the importance of careful inspection of pallets used in the transportation and storage of hazardous materials. Veolia staff will be retrained on performing enhanced quality control measures during the packaging and loading processes to prevent similar incidents in the future.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While staged at yard, a leak was detected coming from trailer. Area was isolated and Environmental Restoration LLC was dispatched to perform cleanup. Upon arrival on site, ERLLC applied absorbent material to the free product beneath trailer, and performed trailer inspection. One 55-gallon drum was discovered at nose of trailer, which appeared to be struck by a nail during transit or loading process. ERLLC utilized absorbent material to clean the trailer floor, overpacked the Ieaking drum, and reloaded trailer. Product was scraped from impacted area and containerized with spent absorbent into one 55-gallon drum. Three drums were generated during response. One overpack drum, which contained the damaged drum, one 55-gallon recovery drum with contaminated cardboard, and one 55-gallon drum of spent absorbents, gravel, and poly sheeting. Free product was contained to immediate area and did not threaten to impact state waters. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column169: On 9/6/2024 at approximately 1115, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 3962724 at the sort facility in Aguadilla, Puerto Rico, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of several packages appearing to be processed through Amazon.   Spillage occurred among the packages, prompting FedEx to further investigate, resulting in the identification of the spilled package as nail polish remover, which was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  Dangerous Goods Administration obtained the safety data sheet of a similar product to verify indentification.   The other packages remain unopened and the contents unknown.   The spilled package was removed from the box and the remainder of the shipment is being held for package retreival.
